<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910821-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>910821-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Burlington Resources   To Buy Properties   From Union Texas</HL><DATE>08/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   BR MEOLY UTH</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)PIPELINE OPERATORS (PIP)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>LOUISIANA (LA)NEW MEXICO (NM)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   SEATTLE -- Burlington Resources Inc. said its oil and gasproducing unit, Meridian Oil Inc., agreed to acquire&quot;substantially all&quot; the North American onshore oil and gasproperties of Union Texas Petroleum Corp. for about $260million.   Burlington Resources said the properties, in Texas,Louisiana, New Mexico and the Rocky Mountains, have recentlybeen producing a daily average of about 6,800 barrels of oiland 48 million cubic feet of natural gas. Proved and probablereserves are equivalent to about 62 million barrels of oil,the company said.</LP><TEXT>   The transaction, which is expected to be completed nextmonth, is subject to conditions, including Federal TradeCommission approval.   In Houston, Union Texas said the sale, which doesn'tinclude its Alaska holdings, is part of its streamliningeffort, a strategy the energy concern adopted after failingin an attempt to sell itself whole. In April, Union Texassold its domestic offshore oil and gas properties to NercoInc. for $475 million. The company said its restructuringplans also include the possible sale of its domestichydrocarbon products businesses.   Union Texas said proceeds from the sale to BurlingtonResources will initially be invested but eventually used forgeneral corporate purposes, including the continuation of itsrestructuring.</TEXT></DOC>